@page "/advanced-features"
@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components
@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Web

<PageTitle>Advanced Markdn Features</PageTitle>

<CascadingValue Value="@_pageMetadata">

<h1 id="advanced-markdn-features">Advanced Markdn Features</h1>
<p>Once you're comfortable with the basics, it's time to explore some of Markdn's more advanced features.</p>
<h2 id="custom-blazor-components-in-markdown">Custom Blazor Components in Markdown</h2>
<p>You can embed custom Blazor components directly in your Markdown:</p>
<pre><code class="language-markdown">&lt;MyCustomComponent Parameter=&quot;value&quot; /&gt;
</code></pre>
<h2 id="dynamic-routing">Dynamic Routing</h2>
<p>Markdn automatically generates routes for your content based on the file structure and frontmatter.</p>
<h2 id="type-safe-frontmatter">Type-Safe Frontmatter</h2>
<p>With Markdn's source generator, you get compile-time type safety for all your frontmatter properties:</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">// This is type-safe!
string title = post.Title;
DateTime pubDate = post.PubDate;
List&lt;string&gt; tags = post.Tags;
</code></pre>
<h2 id="query-and-filter">Query and Filter</h2>
<p>Use LINQ to query your content collections:</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">var recentPosts = contentService
    .GetCollection()
    .Where(p =&gt; p.PubDate &gt; DateTime.Now.AddMonths(-1))
    .OrderByDescending(p =&gt; p.PubDate)
    .Take(5);
</code></pre>
<h2 id="whats-next">What's Next?</h2>
<p>Check out the documentation for more advanced use cases and best practices!</p>


</CascadingValue>

@code {
    private class PageMetadata
    {
        public string? Title { get; set; }
        public string? Slug { get; set; }
        public string? Route { get; set; }
        public string? Summary { get; set; }
        public DateTime? Date { get; set; }
        public List<string>? Tags { get; set; }
        public Dictionary<string, object>? AdditionalData { get; set; }
    }

    private readonly PageMetadata _pageMetadata = new()
    {
        Title = "Advanced Markdn Features",
        Route = "/advanced-features",
        Tags = new List<string> { "advanced", "components", "routing" },
    };

}
